<h2>Standard family package needs</h2>

<p>A standard family package suits homes with several active users. This may include parents working online, children using school platforms, smart TVs, mobile phones, tablets, and occasional guests. The home may stream in high definition, run video calls, use cloud storage, download updates, and support multiple devices at the same time. For many Kenyan households, this is the most realistic residential planning category.</p>

<p>The biggest risk in a standard family home is congestion during peak hours. One person may be on a work meeting, another may be watching YouTube, children may be downloading assignments, and phones may be backing up photos. The package should have enough capacity for simultaneous use, but local Wi-Fi design is just as important. Thick walls, upstairs bedrooms, servant quarters, home offices, and outdoor sitting areas may require mesh Wi-Fi or an additional access point.</p>

<p>Families should also consider basic network management. Create a strong Wi-Fi password, avoid sharing it too widely, and consider a separate guest network if the router supports it. If children use the connection for school, ask whether the router can support parental controls or device scheduling. The best residential package is one that matches how the household actually lives.</p>

<h2>High-use residential package needs</h2>

<p>A high-use residential package is for homes where internet is critical. This includes remote workers, online business owners, content creators, gamers, large families, homes with CCTV, smart home systems, and properties with multiple buildings. The household may need strong upload performance, low latency, wide Wi-Fi coverage, and backup power. A simple plug-and-play approach may not be enough.</p>

<p>High-use homes should plan the local network carefully. Use Ethernet where possible for workstations, smart TVs, network video recorders, or important desks. Add access points for upstairs rooms, home offices, detached units, or outdoor areas. If the home runs CCTV, separate camera traffic from normal browsing where possible. If the connection supports work calls, place the router or access point close enough to the work area to keep signal stable.</p>

<p>These homes should also ask about support and upgrade options before buying. If the service is used for income, online meetings, security, or school, downtime has a cost. Confirm who provides support, how fast they respond, whether they can return for network improvements, and what happens if the package needs to be upgraded later.</p>

<h2>What affects residential package prices?</h2>

