<h2>How residential packages compare with fibre and mobile data</h2>

<p>Fibre is often the best home internet option where it is available, affordable, and reliable. It can provide low latency and strong speeds. The problem is that fibre does not reach every estate, rural home, farm, or holiday property. Some homes wait months for installation, while others are told the nearest fibre route is too far away.</p>

<p>Mobile data is convenient, but it depends on signal strength and tower congestion. A home may get good speeds in the morning and poor speeds in the evening. Thick walls can reduce indoor signal. Data bundles can also become expensive for streaming, online classes, large downloads, and many devices. A 4G or 5G router may work well in one neighbourhood and poorly in another.</p>

<p>Amazon Leo residential internet is most attractive where the household wants a fixed broadband-style connection without waiting for fibre. It can also work as backup for homes that already have fibre but need continuity. To compare providers more broadly, read our internal guide on <a href="/satellite-internet-providers-in-kenya">satellite internet providers in Kenya</a>.</p>

<h2>Speed expectations for home users</h2>

<p>Home users should look beyond download speed. Download speed affects streaming, browsing, updates, and school content. Upload speed affects video calls, cloud backups, WhatsApp media, CCTV, and sending large files. Latency affects gaming, calls, remote work, and how responsive websites feel. A good package balances all three for the home's real activities.</p>

<p>Real performance depends on terminal type, package, network conditions, installation quality, weather, power stability, router quality, and Wi-Fi coverage. If a speed test is done next to the router, it may look good while the bedroom or home office still has weak Wi-Fi. Test from actual usage areas before deciding whether the package is enough.</p>

<p>For more detail, compare our internal page on <a href="/amazon-leo-internet-speeds-in-kenya">Amazon Leo Internet speeds in Kenya</a>. If the speed is poor, troubleshoot in order: check Wi-Fi signal, check device load, check router placement, check terminal obstruction, check power, then review whether the package itself is too small.</p>

