<p>After the first month, review whether the package fits the household. If the connection is stable but some rooms are weak, improve Wi-Fi. If all devices slow down during peak usage, consider package changes or router management. If power cuts interrupt service, add backup power. Package management should be based on evidence, not guesses.</p>

<h2>How to choose the right residential package</h2>

<p>Start with the number of users and devices. Then list the most demanding activities: video calls, online classes, streaming, gaming, CCTV, cloud backups, and remote work. Next, map the house. Identify where the terminal can be mounted, where the router should sit, and which rooms need strong signal. Finally, compare total cost and support quality.</p>

<p>Ask each provider direct questions. What kit is included? What monthly package is recommended? Why is that package suitable for this home? Does the quote include installation? Does it include mounting hardware? Will the installer test every main room? What happens if the first mounting point is blocked? Is support included? Can the package be upgraded later?</p>

