<h2>FAQs about Amazon Leo residential packages in Kenya</h2>

<h3>Which Amazon Leo residential package is best for a normal home?</h3>
<p>The best package depends on the number of users, devices, rooms, and activities. A small household may need a lighter plan, while a family with remote workers, streaming, gaming, online classes, and CCTV may need a stronger package and better Wi-Fi equipment.</p>

<h3>Do residential packages include installation?</h3>
<p>Not always. Some quotes include installation while others only cover equipment or subscription. Always ask whether mounting hardware, transport, labour, cable routing, router setup, and testing are included.</p>

<h3>Can I use Amazon Leo residential internet in rural Kenya?</h3>
<p>Yes. Rural homes are one of the strongest use cases, provided the property has clear sky access, stable mounting, protected cable routing, suitable power, and Wi-Fi coverage inside the home.</p>

<h3>Can one router cover the whole house?</h3>
<p>Sometimes, but not always. Small open-plan homes may be fine with one router. Maisonettes, large homes, thick walls, detached rooms, and outdoor spaces may need mesh Wi-Fi or additional access points.</p>

<h3>Is Amazon Leo residential internet better than mobile data?</h3>
<p>It can be better where mobile signal is weak, congested, or expensive for heavy use. Mobile data may still work well in some areas. The best choice depends on your location, usage, cost, and reliability needs.</p>

<h3>Can a residential package support working from home?</h3>
<p>Yes, if the package, router placement, Wi-Fi coverage, upload speed, latency, and power backup are planned properly. Remote workers should test video calls and cloud tools from the actual work area.</p>

<h2>Final thoughts</h2>

<p>Amazon Leo Internet residential packages in Kenya should be chosen around real household needs, not only the lowest price or biggest advertised speed. The right package is the one that supports your number of users, your rooms, your daily activities, your installation conditions, and your support expectations. For many homes, installation quality and Wi-Fi design will matter as much as the package name.</p>

